                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18200517-6-off31 t18200517-6-crimeloc34"></join>. On the 10th of May, about eight o'clock in the evening I missed the copper pot, which was stolen from an out-house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200517-6-person119">
                  JOHN 
                  INGRAM
               <interp inst="t18200517-6-person119" type="surname" value="INGRAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-6-person119" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-6-person119" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman of Shadwell. About four o'clock in the morning I saw the prisoner coming along with the pot, and asked him what he had got there? he said it was a pot, which had been sent him from Manchester. I took him to the watch-house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200517-6-person120">
                  JOHN 
                  JOHNSON
               <interp inst="t18200517-6-person120" type="surname" value="JOHNSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-6-person120" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-6-person120" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a headborough. The prisoner was brought to the watch-house; he said he had been drinking with some men, and that the pot was left for him by the Manchester carrier. I believed distress had drove him to it. He afterwards said he took it from a little house through the turnpike, where his master lived.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18200517-6-verdict35" type="verdictDescription">
